node.text: Honored to be featured in the latest episode of #transparencytuesday by @volvic, a serie taking us on their journey of transformation focusing on protecting nature and people’s strength. I started partnering with Volvic when I discovered what they're doing to preserve the natural resources and their commitment towards a more sustainable production mode that I hope inspires many other big (and small!) companies to follow. We cannot think about humans vs nature but realize that we're all one together. #Volvic @loopsider

node.text:
Last weeks conditions of very sticky snow, despite how dry it was, drove me towards an idea I had in mind for the last years. Romsdalshorn is mostly a rocky summit but in a combination of the Halls Renne gully and the east face where the normal route goes it’s possible to ski from the col with only a 10m traverse and a 30m abseil. A great downhill with ambiance assured!
.
🎥 @gopro 🎿 @salomon

node.text:
Sport is for me a way to explore and find self knowledge. In this quest, last year I spent 24h climbing with my skis to do the most elevation I could. This year I came down from the mountains to try my endurance on flat ground, running for a full day on a track. It will be fun/painful to see how far I can run in 24h.

Exact dates of the attempt are still being decided, we’ll announce it in the next few days. Stay tuned & for more information check my bio 👆  #KilianPhantasm24h @salomon

node.title: HOW FAR CAN I RUN ON FLAT GROUND IN 24 HOURS?

node.text:
Many times in the past I’ve been doubting if I should talk about climate and environmental issues on social media. Fear of criticism for talking about while having not the most sustainable lifestyle, writing about subjects where I’m not expert, etc. But it’s something I care about, that it’s recurrent in my private conversations and because I believe it’s better to be an imperfect advocate that none. To start reducing my footprint I should understand it better from all the angles, accepting my ignorance in many of the fields.

To feel more comfortable and confident to talk about subjects like carbon emissions, regenerative agriculture, biodiversity, policy, industry footprint, etc. I’ve been chatting with many experts in the past months. I want to thank all of them to enlighten me, and also to @huwmjames who has been the soul (and hardworker) behind all of this to bring this conversations to all of you in a platform where you can find them in different formats ( podcast, short videos, livestreams, animations) 

You can tape www.athleteclimateacademy.com (link in my bio) to watch and listen to it!

node.text:
Here a carousel of some of the “trails” I’ve training the last month.

Since I was back from Himalayas I’ve been focusing on training for trail running. After last year’s injury problems I was a bit afraid of getting back there when starting to put big charges of running, but - with a probably most suited combination for my adaptations of mountain + trail + flat sessions - so far it’s been working very well. True thing is that when you train hard normally you don’t take pictures, so I hope the emptiness of phone photo gallery equals to fullness of capacities gained 😜

node.text:
Today IOC assembly approved that ski mountaineering will be a Olympic in @milanocortina2026 ! 💥 

This is great news for the sport and the athletes and all the skimo mouvement! Congrats to @ismf_world_cup and all the people who’ve been working for this during many years 👊

With all the the excitement, I still hold a divided opinion on that. In one side, as a sports fan I love watching big sport events like world championships and Olympic Games where you can smell the pressure on the air. As an athlete, the dream of winning a gold medal is something that any sport kid has dreamed once. As someone who’s been on the circuit for almost 20 years I see how becoming olympic can help the development of the discipline in different countries and have more financial support for national teams from governments.

On the other side, I’ve seen how many times a sport has changed its format until denaturing its core values, I see that the Olympic disciplines will be sprint, mixed relay and individual race, I hope that the mountaineering aspect that is the heart of the sport doesn’t disappear on its way to be more spectator friendly creating a separation between the amateurs of the sport and the pro competitors.

Well, it will be interesting to see how this journey unfolds! Today is a day to celebrate for the many people who has dreamed for decades this to come 👊

📷 @jocelynchavy

With so many friends racing in two of my favorite races it was hard to stay home doing a easy training ;) as a “picat” I wanted to feel some of the heavy lactic legs and blood taste in the mouth too,

This week end is @hardrock100run one of the most beautiful ultratrails, with a incredible atmosphere. To all the racers I wish for you to kiss the rock!

In the dolomites, the classic @dolomythsrun will be another great race with the fastest skyrunners! Good luck to everyone!

With a feel of the San Juans and the Dolomites I was pushing hard today in 2 of my favorite summits. Going for my first time under 1h in the vesteggen at Store Vengetind and for my second time under 30’ at Romsdalshorn :)

node.text: As outdoor athletes we spend a lot of time in wilderness. We might be aware of climate change, biodiversity loss, industry or pollution problems but we maybe don’t have the scientific literacy to understand it better and to share it with others. When @huwmjames came with an idea of making a platform for connecting athletes - and any outdoor enthusiast- with environmental scientists in each field I couldn’t but start working with him and other athletes and scientists to bring on the Athlete Climate Academy. Stay tuned at @kilianjornetfoundation and @anturuseducation for more infos soon! 👉 link at bio!

node.text:
Some time ago I got a message in social media from a person who had been running several marathons and ultratrails. He was asking for the track of a route he saw I did, but could not find it anywhere. The route indeed was a ski crossing linking several steep skiing lines with alpine climbs in Mont Blanc range I had done that spring. He wanted to run it on august as training for a ultra since he would be in the region and it looked super nice.
Even if this might sound extreme, it’s too common to see athletes without a mountaineering experience to plan or jump into mountaineering activities without any knowledge of the risks and dangers they might be facing. And often it happens nothing, but without noticing they’re close to big consequences. A change of weather, getting to a place that requires technical capacities that we don’t have or missing resources in form of gear or knowledge to scape or to progress is frequent when we do adventures in mountains. To familiarize oneself with the lecture of the grading systems ( what does it means PD, D… WI4, V+…) to understand if we have the capacities to try or not a route and to get the experience to read the weather forecasts and the weather signs as well as the use of gear and different solutions to solve problems IS mandatory to avoid problems. And for that it doesn’t matter how strong or fast we are, but as all the technical activities, we need to learn it, in a alpine club, with mountain guides or mentors. I think trail running is missing a important point on proclaiming every other race the “hardest race” because they are long, because they’re hot or because marketing but it isn’t any difficulty grading so runners can have an idea of they technical level on trails ( some conversations today lead to misunderstandings when 2 different athletes are talking about a “technical” run one might be thinking of something like utmb and the other of something like Kima…) and that before entering the mountaineering world and understanding it’s proper scale of difficulties and exposures.

📸 @mattibernitz
